{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531354"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.13,0.54,0.17,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57195"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7284"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42654"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"5570"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17794"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57195"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after ingesting an unknown quantity of amitriptyline tablets three hours ago in a suicide attempt. She has a history of depression but no other medical conditions and usually only takes amitriptyline. On examination, she appears drowsy but rousable to touch. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her pupils are dilated. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with a QRS duration of 140 ms. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activated charcoal","Intubation and mechanical ventilation","Sodium bicarbonate","Calcium carbonate","Noradrenaline infusion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of significant tricyclic antidepressant toxicity, including altered mental status, tachycardia, hypotension, and importantly, QRS prolongation on ECG. The wide QRS complex (\u003E100 ms) indicates sodium channel blockade and risk of life-threatening arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it treats the cardiac conduction abnormalities by increasing serum pH and sodium concentration. This reduces tricyclic binding to sodium channels and helps prevent ventricular arrhythmias. The target pH is 7.50-7.55.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E can reduce drug absorption if given within 1-2 hours of ingestion. This patient is not in the ideal window for activated charcoal, and given her drowsiness and unprotected airway, this carries a significant risk of aspiration and should not be the first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E may be required for persistent hypotension after sodium bicarbonate administration, but addressing the cardiac conduction abnormalities takes priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and mechanical ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered early in the course of treatment, particularly if there is deteriorating consciousness or need for aggressive hyperventilation. However, sodium bicarbonate administration is the more urgent intervention for QRS prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium carbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line treatment for tricyclic overdose. While calcium may be used for some drug-induced arrhythmias, there is no evidence supporting its routine use in tricyclic toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important aspects of management include continuous cardiac monitoring, securing IV access, and frequent reassessment as patients can deteriorate rapidly. Benzodiazepines may be needed for seizures, and admission to intensive care is usually required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sodium bicarbonate is first-line therapy for tricyclic antidepressant toxicity to treat QRS widening and prevent arrhythmias.","Intubation should be considered early in tricyclic overdose due to rapid deterioration and need for hyperventilation.","Activated charcoal can be given if the patient presents within 2 hours and has a protected airway."],"references":["Kerr GW, McGuffie AC, Wilkie S. Tricyclic antidepressant overdose: a review. Emergency Medicine Journal 2001;18:236-241.","Khalid MM, Waseem M. Tricyclic Antidepressant Toxicity. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430931/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42654"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42654"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T11:08:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T11:12:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7284"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57195"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":